A: The problem is that you are writing the strings without a line break. The BufferedReader reads until it finds a line separator, which it doesn't find because you didn't write one.
You should write a line separator after each string. The line separator is platform-dependent, but you can use "\n" or "\r\n" (for Windows) or "\r" (for Mac).
Here is the corrected code:
PrintWriter printWriter = ...
printWriter.write("1\n");
printWriter.write("2\n");
printWriter.write("3\n");

Or if you want to write all the strings in one go:
PrintWriter printWriter = ...
printWriter.write("1\n2\n3\n");

Then, when you read the lines, you should read them one by one:
ServerSocket serverSocket = ...
Socket socket = serverSocket.accept();
BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(socket.getInputStream()));
System.out.println(bufferedReader.readLine());
System.out.println(bufferedReader.readLine());
System.out.println(bufferedReader.readLine());

This will print each line separately.

